<td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%">
<p>Well, 2 things, first running depends on who's the peeler, and what kind of mob it is. For warriors, a running caster can make the job almost impossible, but if the peeler is a paladin or SK, you CAN run, just run in front of them, so they can target the mob. If you have crowd control, kite the mob in front of the chanter/bard so they can target. <br /> <br />My cleric has decent equipment for a non raid cleric (1300+ac, 4900hp) with typical group buffs. Even with that, if I stand still while being hit, I live approximately 5 seconds in a hard ldon. Now, if its a normal LDON, I can either just channel a root through the mobs hits, offtank it myself, or stand around playing gems until someone peels it. But thats really not an option if fighting something that hits hard. <br /> <br />ALso, if you WANT the casters to hold still, USE SHIELD. It baffles me how few warriors actually use the shield disc, even though it significantly increases the odds that the caster will survive til you peel. If one person repeatedly gets aggro HOTKEY the shield to that person. <br /> <br />Also, I disagree with the person who said that once you get CH, it will be your most used spell. Once again, thats very situational. I was in a sewer trial in GoD, we were there several hours total, and I doubt I cast CH 1/3 as often as I did my faster heals. Sure, I'd have LIKED to cast CH, but those mobs were taking the tank down to 50% so fast, he would have been dead before CH went off, even if I started when the mob got its first hit in. <br /> <br />Remember CH is ALWAYS 10 seconds to cast. The fast heals can be taken down to VERY short cast times, with BoR and a spell haste item. Plus with IH items and AA the healing power of those spells can be juiced way up. <br /> <br /></p>
